body:
When instantiating two parameterized extern modules, both map to the same module which causes generation to fail if port types are not the same between the two parameterizations.

Minimal example demonstrating problem:
```
@module
class MyModule:
    clk = Input(types.i1)
    data_in = Input(dim(6))

    @generator
    def construct(mod):
        inst_a = ExternMod(DW=2)(
            clk=mod.clk,
            data_in=mod.data_in[0:2]
        )
        inst_b = ExternMod(DW=4)(
            clk=mod.clk,
            data_in=mod.data_in[2:6]
        )
        return {}

@externmodule
def ExternMod(DW: int):

    class Mod:
        clk = Input(types.i1)
        data_in = Input(dim(DW))

    return Mod

```

Multiple parameterizations of the same extern module will still map to the same pycde module object. The module object tracks a single `extern_mod` variable which is ultimately used for all parameterizations. One solution is to track parameters and have a separate `extern_mod` object for each parameter set.
